	   <tr><td colspan=2>I just wanted to clear up a few errors and oversights in this post, since the author is toting it as the be-all and end-all newbie guide.<br><br>First off, as a magician you are specifically a pet class.&nbsp;&nbsp;As such, it is your responsibility to get to know your pets and their capabilities early on in the game.  This is the reason you're given access to all four from the very beginning.  You MUST purchase all four pets and become accustomed to them.  A mage who doesn't know his pets is a bad mage and will be recognized as such by the people he groups with.<br><br>Secondly, rusties equipped by pets do nothing more than look cool.  They do not, in any way enhance your pet's fighting skills.  Even when your pet (at level 24) becomes capable of dual-wielding, he will do the same damage with the same delay barehanded.  The only weapons that will enhance his fighting skills are weapons that process (i.e. velium weapons), and even with these only if he's been buffed for dexterity.<br><br>Thirdly, Evocation!  Evocation!  Evocation!  You must start early in always keeping this particular skill maxxed at all times.  At earlier levels, it won't mean much.  But once you become able to specialize it will make a huge difference in your effectiveness at later levels.  Although there are some who disagree, I think most mages feel that it's silly and wasteful to specialize in anything other than Evocation (there is an argument in favor of specializing in conjuration - but I personally feel it's a losing argument).  Therefore, your 'shock' spells should be used sparingly.  The 'bolt' spells are more difficult to use (because they require a clear line of sight), but will be more useful to you in the long run.  'Shock' spells are really only useful when it's impossible to get a clear line of sight (i.e. when a MOB is surrounded by tanks and you can't position yourself correctly to get a clear line of sight).  If you've specialized in evocation and have this skill maxxed, you will be incredibly powerful in your later years!<br><br>And finally, Research!  Research!  Research!  The suggestion that you might want to 'get by' without researching all your pets is nonsense.  If you plan to do anything aside from sitting in one place and killing the same thing over and over again, you'll need all your pets.  Different dungeons require different pets and different MOBs (which have different resists) require different pets.  Also, if you've ignored your research, you're gonna spend a fortune buying your higher level spells from other mages.  I personally charge 30 p for each Lvl. 20 - 29 researched spell that I sell, 50 p for each 30 - 39, and 100 p for each 40 - 49.  (This is on top of the player having to supply me with the research components.)  My justification for this is that I spend my time and effort working on my research skill - something the other mage was too lazy to do.  I should be paid well for this.  (At higher levels, most mages have come to terms with how important it is to have ALL your pets and are generally happy to pay my price.)<br><br>P. S.  NEVER rely completely on the advice of just one person!  There's more than one way to skin a cat (or a kobold...or a gnoll...or...)<br>&nbsp;<br>Dovilo Ravenstear<br>52 Mage of the Tribunal<br>Tuatha De Danann<br><br><br>Have Pet.&nbsp;&nbsp;Will Travel.</td></tr>
